metadata.name: Rearranged #138
metadata.description:
Rearranged is an invitation to engage in an exploration of aesthetics within the constraints of the generated token. 

Each piece has 4 layers. Each layer can be independently rotated by 90 degrees clockwise by clicking 1,2,3 or 4 on the keyboard. Some changes are subtle. Some are surprising. 

's' on the keyboard will scramble all of the rotations.
'r' will reset to the original artwork.

You are invited to: 
arrange a more aesthetically pleasing piece than the original;
scramble the artwork and use the number keys to return it to its original state;
work out which shapes have been erased from each layer.

And of course there is also a gorgeous gradient illusion made of solid-colour filled tessellating shapes. 

3 tessellations of varying sizes, 12 layouts with random elements, 14 palettes.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Lineage #177
metadata.description:
Lineage is a collaboration between Tim Maxwell and Twistie that attempts to bridge the gap between traditional and generative art.
256 outputs are generated using 100% JavaScript + p5js, written by Twistie, in the distinctive style of Tim Maxwell. The code tries to replicate not only the style, but also the process and inaccuracies that go into a drawing.

Each iteration has a unique title. 
All 256 rendered outputs and their respective titles will be displayed in high quality on https://twistie.org/lineage. 

10 lucky owners will have their iteration hand drawn and signed. They will each receive the physical 1/1 as well as an NFT version.

Press 's' on keyboard to save in high-res. This is how the art is intended to be viewed.

Hardware acceleration on Chromium-based browsers can impact performance!

metadata.name: PXL #137
metadata.description:
PXL is an exploration of video synthesis, each pixel containing 4 cells phasing between two values. This effect creates all sorts of interesting effects when scaled up, so enjoy the completely unique effect your optical illusion generates.

There is a 5% chance to generate a wave glitch in your pattern.

Color palettes:
80% Normal (Randomly Generated)
10% Monochrome
5% RGB
5% CMYK

Press 's' to save a png
Press 'm' to save a 10s mp4 (can take up to 2m to render)

metadata.name: Proto alphabet #80
metadata.description:
For more than 4000 years, before Lineal A in Crete, proto alphabets were created. They freed man from the chains of evolution and gave a way to record the rhythm of the passage of time.

As recursion generates a grammar, recursion generates the strokes that shape the following proto alphabets, which attempt to record the passage of time.

Time is the substance I am made of. Time is a river which sweeps me along, but I am the river; it is a tiger which destroys me, but I am the tiger; it is a fire which consumes me, but I am the fire. - Jorge Luis Borges


Desde hace más de 4000 años, antes Lineal A en Creta, proto alfabetos fueron creados. Liberaron al hombre de las cadenas de la evolución y dieron una forma para registrar el ritmo del paso del tiempo.

Como la recursividad genera una gramática, la recursividad genera los trazos que dan forma a los siguientes proto alfabetos, los cuales intentan registrar el paso del tiempo.

El tiempo es la sustancia de que estoy hecho. El tiempo es un río que me arrebata, pero yo soy el río; es un tigre que me destroza, pero yo soy el tigre; es un fuego que me consume, pero yo soy el fuego. - Jorge Luis Borges

metadata.name: GRAPHEME #65
metadata.description:
Released on the occasion of the Tribute to Herbert W. Franke. 
www.tribute-hwf.com

“One criterion for art involves the process used by the artist for shaping the work. In the special case of mathematically supported fine art, the artmaking process occurs in a mathematically defined operation that allows the generation and transformation of images, methods used for picture processing.” - Herbert W. Franke

I first came across Franke’s ‘Ornamental Alphabets’ in his book 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘎𝘳𝘢𝘱𝘩𝘪𝘤𝘴 - 𝘊𝘰𝘮𝘱𝘶𝘵𝘦𝘳 𝘈𝘳𝘵, and was intrigued with the idea of using a simple letterform to explore different generative image processing techniques. 

I’ve used letters and writing in my work for a long time, both with letterpress printing and in my asemic poetry programs. With asemic writing, I generate unrecognizable letters to reference text, and here I use recognizable letterforms removed from their typical function as language signifiers. 

My goal with this project was to build as much texture and layering as possible by warping and collaging the letters together in various ways. The font I’m using is a design I made years ago to supplement my wood type collection for printing. I really enjoyed being able to bring that part of my past work into my generative art practice. 

Each image is composed of the letters found in the hash for that piece, divided into either vowels or consonants. The program builds on a technique I’ve used before, where I generate an image to an off-screen canvas and then dive through the pixels to pull out the color and form I want to surface in the final image.

25% of the primary sales will be donated on-chain to the Foundation Herbert W. Franke. These funds will be used by ZKM Karlsruhe to digitize Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. Any additional funds raised will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.

- Press “R” to increase the pixel density and reload the image (this can be render intensive and will create a really large file suitable for printing)
- Press “S” to save a copy

Made with p5js
Artist: Sarah Ridgley
October, 2022

metadata.name: thébaïde #97
metadata.description:
“Thébaïde” is a french word for wild place, remote and peaceful, where to live in a calm retreat. It's also simply a desert and a synonym of solitude. It comes from Thebaid, an arid region of ancient Egypt and Thebes was the capital.

“thébaïde” is my debut on fx(hash), almost one year since my first works minted on Objkt (a series of Indian ink drawings, in January 2022). After learning the basics of creative coding recently, and a few works with this technique, I decided to create a first generative project. With "thébaïde" I chose to express the minimalist and narrative aspects of my artistic approach (though the title and concept emerged at the end). Gradually the work was resonating with philosophical matters I'm obsessed with since years: time, emptiness, human condition, erosion, desire, chance, combining them into a visual metaphor. The view of a vast area, a changing silhouette, an impenetrable monolith or an opening to elsewhere or nothing, day and night and day and night and dawn and dusk — few elements able to compose a meditative and lasting tableau of questions and feelings.

Press “s” in live mode to save the work.
Made with p5js | 2023
Png | 2000 px x 2000 px | 72 ppi

www.antoniowerli.com

metadata.name: Rings - v2 (remastered) #12
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Rings was originally published as Project #10921 on March 19, 2022.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/10921)
Due to a technical issue, Project #10921 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________

Rings project in its first version was made at an unfavorable time and had technical problems that resulted in outputs far from my idealization as a creator. This re-edition opportunity allowed me not only to correct the offline library access problems, but also to implement what I actually envisioned in this work.

Technically, Rings consists of the aesthetic result of the radial accumulation of simple shapes (circles, squares and triangles) acting as small particles that follow polar functions to form concentric patterns that are not always so symmetrical.

While the backgrounds are filled with more sober colors, the front palettes are the result of the trichromatic combination inspired by Brazilian biomes, in homage to our rich geographic diversity. The trail left by these particles allows the formation of a type of "brush texture" on the canvas, while shadows and white dots give the necessary finish, helping with depth perception.

And again....palletes carefully chosen.



FEATURES:
> Foreground Palette: Pampas Grassland, Cerrado Savanna, Amazon Rainforest, Atlantic Coast, Caatinga Dry Forest, Pantanal Wetlands, Atlantic Forest
> Background Palette: 5 'sober' colors.
> Radius Shape: Round, Oval-X, Oval-Y.
> Trail Rate: 0.25, 0.33, 0.5, 1.0 Hz.
> Total Particles Amount: 400, 600, 800, 1000.
> Offscreen Frames: 200, 300, 400, 500, 600. 

RARITY BONUS:
> Discover!

INTERACTIVE MODS, PRESS ANYTIME:
> "S" to save a .png of your canvas (in Open Live).

Made with p5.js

_______________________________
Creator: Kukuti
Mar2022 -> Dec2022
License: NFT 2.0

metadata.name: Digital Gardens #248
metadata.description:
Digital Gardens are places of magic and wonder, where you can connect with your inner nature and take a deep breath. Digital Gardens are a refuge from the world outside. A sanctuary for the mind, body, and soul. But they are also a place of play and exploration. It is a space where you can let your imagination run wild, creating and discovering new things.
Digital Gardens brings to life the minimalistic essence of Detegus’ art and the abstract and rational art of Alfredo Boaron.
The gardens are generated from a recursive function dividing the space at each iteration with a proportion that follows the Fibonacci succession and randomly stops after some iterations. At each recursion the canvas is divided into two pieces following the proportion of two consecutive Fibonacci numbers [1 to 144].
The minimalistic visual effect is then personalized by the palettes of 15 artists who embraced the invitation to give their personal contribution to the collection. The palette name and the author name is displayed in the features along with the Fibonacci numbers ratio, the colors number vs the total palette color number, the background color, the total number of rectangles and the depth level of recursion achieved by the algorithm.
Immerse yourself in this generative project, inspired by geometrism and abstract expressionism. 
Lose yourself in the beauty of a digital garden.

metadata.name: KINJO! #94
metadata.description:
A celebration of my 1 year in the Tezos art space, KINJO is an experiment in pure abstraction and randomness. With a simple grid at its core, this piece attempts to play with lively colors, completely unique variations, and host the nice surprises that randomness can bring.

My intention when starting to work in the Tezos space was to play with the surrender of control in art, that idea had always fascinated me. In the beginning it was working with GAN, digitally painting a piece or processing my own photography, and sending it through my own frankensteined colab notebook. I was creating something and then trusting a process to rip it apart and create something new. I moved on to the Ganerations project, which was essentially gen art in layered pngs and processed through my GAN notebook. I found generative art and fxHash shortly after and have been incredibly thankful for the community here, as well as inspired every day by the new approaches I see from both new and established artists on the platform. I'm learning every day.

Gen art is the perfect place for me to express myself and explore the themes of control and trust with my work, and I thank you all for following along and supporting my work :)

metadata.name: Gentrax EP #21
metadata.description:
Gentrax EP is a generative audiovisual artwork. Each iteration produces a generative house/garage track ~3 minutes in length while drawing out accompanying artwork. Live piece is aspect ratio agnostic and scales to any window size, but an aspect of 1:1.414 is preferred and can be set with an URL parameter.

Audio controls:
1-7: Channel mutes/unmutes
a: Filter up 
z: Filter down
c: Flanger on/off
v: Reverb (cycle thru three settings)
q: Switch bassline octave&seq (cycle thru three settings)
b: Portamento on/off

Visual controls: 
p: Fast forward to final artwork
o: Save canvas

Url parameters: 
&w=800 : Set width of canvas. If aspect ratio is not defined, artwork will be in preferred aspect ratio (1.41414)
&a=1.5 : Set aspect ratio. number <1 = Wide canvas
&wl=1 : Locks canvas aspect ratio to preferred 


made with p5.js & tone.js
Using tonejs synthesis for bass plus oneshot samples from various drum machines & Alpha Juno 2
<3

CC-BY-NC-SA 4.0
